body:
Macro spans cause suggestions that, once applied, break other code.

```rust
struct X;

struct Wrapper<T>(T);

macro_rules! m {
    () => { X };
}

fn main() {
    let _: Wrapper<X> = m!();
    let _: X = m!();
}
```

Suggests:
```
help: try wrapping the expression in `Wrapper`
   |
6  |     () => { Wrapper(X) };
   |             ++++++++ +
```

Once applied, causes this error:
```
error[E0308]: mismatched types
  --> src/main.rs:6:13
   |
6  |     () => { Wrapper(X) };
   |             ^^^^^^^^^^ expected struct `X`, found struct `Wrapper`
...
11 |     let _: X = m!();
   |            -   ---- in this macro invocation
   |            |
   |            expected due to this
   |
   = note: expected struct `X`
              found struct `Wrapper<X>`
```

This has some considerations:
1. We could suppress this suggestion if it comes from a macro, which "fixes" this issue, but ideally we'd be suggesting "`Wrapper(m!())`" in the first case.
2. This is a general issue -- while we could fix it in this one case, that's more of a bandaid and I could probably come up with 5 other cases similar to this.
3. Sometimes changing the macro _is_ the correct solution.
